{"title_page": "BASEketball", "text_new": "{{short description|1998 American sports comedy film directed by David Zucker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = BASEketball\n| image = baseketball.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director =  [[David Zucker (director)|David Zucker]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* David Zucker\n* Robert LoCash\n* Gil Netter<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n}}\n| writers =  {{Plainlist|\n* David Zucker\n* Robert LoCash\n* Jeff Wright\n* [[Lewis Friedman]]<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trey Parker]]<!-- Do not list actors that are not included in the poster -->\n* [[Matt Stone]]\n* [[Yasmine Bleeth]]\n* [[Jenny McCarthy]]\n* [[Robert Vaughn]]\n* [[Ernest Borgnine]]\n* [[Dian Bachar]]\n}}\n| music =  [[Ira Newborn|James Ira Newborn]]<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| cinematography =  Steven Mason<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| editing = [[Jeffrey Reiner]]\n| studio =  [[Universal Pictures]]<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| distributor = Universal Pictures<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|title=BASEKetball (1998)|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/60640?cxt=filmography|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|1998|07|31}}\n| runtime = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 103:20--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/baseketball-1970-2 | title=''Baseketball'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| country = United States<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| language = English\n| budget = $23 million\n| gross = $7 million {{small|(U.S. and Canada)}}<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=baseketball.htm|title=BASEketball (1998)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''BASEketball''''' is a 1998 American [[sports comedy]] film co-written and directed by [[David Zucker (director)|David Zucker]] and starring ''[[South Park]]'' creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]], along with [[Yasmine Bleeth]], [[Jenny McCarthy]], [[Robert Vaughn]], [[Ernest Borgnine]], and [[Dian Bachar]]. \n\nThe film follows the history of the sport of the same name (created by Zucker years earlier),{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} from its invention by the lead characters as a game they could win against more [[Sportsperson|athletic]] types, to its development as a nationwide [[Sports league|league]] sport and a target of corporate sponsorship.\n\nThis is the only work involving Parker and Stone that was neither written, directed, nor produced by them, although Zucker himself has stated that Parker and Stone contributed innumerable suggestions for the film, most of which were used.\n\n==Plot==\nLoser best friends Joe \"Coop\" Cooper and Doug Remer [[gate crashing|gate crash]] a high-school reunion and are shunned by their more mature (and successful) classmates. They find themselves outside drinking beer and shooting a basketball when two classmates challenge them to a game. After seeing that their opponents are very good at basketball, they say they will only play a game they picked up in the streets (while secretly inventing the rules as they play, based on both basketball and baseball). After winning, they decide to refine the rules to the game and Coop makes the first BASEketball out of a [[La-Z-Boy]] chair. Their friend, Kenny \"Squeak\" Scolari, tags along and the sport becomes very popular in the neighborhood over the next six months.\n\nBusinessman Ted Denslow meets Coop and Remer and proposes the creation of the National BASEketball League (NBL) along with numerous rules in place to prevent its decline: teams cannot switch cities, players cannot be traded, individuals cannot make money via corporate sponsorship deals, and it is completely open to anyone who wants to play, with Denslow stating that \"anyone can be a sports' hero\". Coop initially hesitates, but quickly accepts the opportunity at hand.\n\nFive years later, the NBL is in full swing with teams, fans, stadiums, and a major championship, the Denslow Cup. Denslow is owner of the Milwaukee Beers, Coop and Remer's team. During the championship game, Denslow dies from choking on a hot dog, causing Coop to miss his shot and costing the Beers the game. Denslow's [[Will and testament|will]] names Coop as owner of the Beers for one year on the condition that they win the next Denslow Cup; otherwise, ownership reverts to Denslow's widow Yvette. Coop declares Remer part owner of the team, and they come to meet Jenna Reed, head of the Dream Come True Foundation, and Joey, one of the children in her care and an avid fan of BASEketball.\n\nBaxter Cain, owner of the Dallas Felons, wants to remove Denslow's rules preventing [[monetization]] of the sport, but could not while Denslow was alive. However, Coop refuses to accept any changes; Cain partners with Yvette as he tries to make the Beers lose the next Denslow Cup so she will own the team.\n\nCain cuts the funding to Jenna's foundation to get Coop and Remer to adopt a clothing line; Coop is against it, but Remer agrees and becomes obsessed with his newfound status. After the semifinals, Cain informs Coop and Remer that the clothing line has been produced through [[child labor]] in [[Calcutta]]; if the public finds out, the team and Jenna's foundation will be ruined. Cain blackmails Coop and Remer into losing or forfeiting the Denslow Cup game or he will inform the public. Jenna learns about the scandal and breaks up with Coop as Coop and Remer blame each other for the predicament.\n\nWith their friendship in shambles, Coop goes to Calcutta, aiming to resolve the situation by replacing the child workers with adults. Making it back to the championship game just as it begins, Coop still blames Remer and the Beers perform abysmally; by the seventh-inning stretch, the Beers are down 16\u20130. Having had enough of Coop and Remer's fighting, Squeak gives the stadium an impassioned speech, reminding Coop and Remer where they came from, how much they changed everyone else's lives, and what they risk losing. Moved, Coop and Remer reconcile their differences as Yvette breaks off her alliance with Cain. After shifting their focus back in the game, they are poised to win when Coop's La-Z-Boy pops. Coop is distraught until Joey brings him a new BASEketball made from a [[Barcalounger]]. After a harrowing last throw, they win the Denslow Cup. Jenna forgives Coop as Yvette makes out with Remer.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Trey Parker]] as Joe \"Coop/Airman\" Cooper\n* [[Matt Stone]] as Doug \"Sir Swish\" Remer\n* [[Dian Bachar]] as Kenny \"Squeak/Little Bitch\" Scolari\n* [[Yasmine Bleeth]] as Jenna Reed\n* [[Jenny McCarthy]] as Yvette Denslow\n* [[Ernest Borgnine]] as Ted Denslow\n* [[Robert Vaughn]] as Baxter Cain\n* [[Trevor Einhorn]] as Joey Thomas\n* [[Francis X. McCarthy]] as Dr. Kaiser (credited as Frank McCarthy) \n* [[Bob Costas]] as Himself\n* [[Al Michaels]] as Himself\n\n[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Dale Earnhardt]], [[Reggie Jackson]], [[Jim Lampley]], [[Kenny Mayne]], [[Tim McCarver]], [[Pat O'Brien (radio and television personality)|Pat O'Brien]], [[Dan Patrick]], [[Reel Big Fish]], [[Victoria Silvstedt]], and [[Robert Stack]] make cameo appearances as themselves. [[Greg Grunberg]], [[Kevin Michael Richardson]], and [[Peter \"Navy\" Tuiasosopo|Peter Tuiasosopo]] also make cameos as athletes.\n\nZucker had wanted [[Chris Farley]] to play the lead role, before casting Parker and Stone due to their work ''[[South Park]]'' becoming a huge hit. The duo agreed to do the movie under the assumption that their show would have been canceled by the time filming began.<ref>http://www.aintitcool.com/node/1742 </ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack featured a bouncy ska cover of Norwegian band [[a-ha]]'s signature single \"[[Take On Me]]\" by [[Reel Big Fish]]. The band also appears as the live entertainment at the home stadium of the Milwaukee Beers, playing \"Take On Me\" and several of their other songs.<ref>[http://80smusicchannel.blogspot.com/2008/10/ha-take-on-me-1985.html 80s Music Channel: Take On Me]</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 42%, with an average rating of 4.98/10, based on 50 reviews from critics. The website's \"Critics Consensus\" is that the film \"isn't just a succession of fouls thanks to the comedic zip of David Zucker's direction, but sophomoric gags and a lack of performance hustle by Trey Parker and Matt Stone makes this satire a clumsy bunt\".<ref>{{cite web |title=BASEketball (1998) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/baseketball |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 38 out of 100, based on reviews from 18 critics, indicating \"Generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |title= BASEketball 1998 |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/baseketball |website= [[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade B on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nIn a positive review with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Leonard Klady said ''BASEketball'' \"has the heightened entertainment challenge of presenting an invented sport ... The film's physical comedy should translate well internationally and chalk up high scores on video\".<ref name=\"klady\">{{cite web |last= Klady |first= Leonard |title=BASEketball |url=https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/baseketball-1200454253/ |website=Variety |date= July 30, 1998 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> The film was awarded four stars out of five by ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's [[Ian Freer]], who called it funny but described the humor as sometimes hit-and-miss.<ref name=\"freer\">{{cite web |last= Freer |first= Ian |title=BASEketball Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/baseketball/review/ |website=Empire |date=September 8, 2006 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Jack Mathews labeled the film as sleep-inducing and \"by far the most inane and badly written of the comedies made by any of the creators of the classic 1980 sendup ''[[Airplane!]]''\".<ref name=\"jack\">{{cite web |last= Mathews |first= Jack |title=Sophomoric 'BASEketball' Leaves Comedy on the Bench |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jul/31/entertainment/ca-8698 |website=Los Angeles Times |date=July 31, 1998 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Michael O'Sullivan in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' called the film \"dark, dull, witless and hobbled by poor comic timing,\" comparing its gross-out humor unfavorably to that of ''[[There's Something About Mary]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last= O'Sullivan |first= Michael |title='BASEketball' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/movies/reviews/baseketballosullivan.htm?noredirect=on |website=Washington Post |date=July 31, 1998 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] echoed this sentiment in his negative review in the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', giving the film one and a half stars out of four and saying the film \"tries to buy laughs with puerile shocks\".<ref>{{cite web |date=July 31, 1998 |last= Ebert |first= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |title=Baseketball Movie Review & Film Summary (1998) |url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/baseketball-1998 |work= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate=January 10, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nFor their roles in the film, Yasmine Bleeth and Jenny McCarthy were nominated at the [[1998 Golden Raspberry Awards]], for the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress|Worst Actress]] and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] awards, respectively. Bleeth lost to the [[Spice Girls]] (for ''[[Spice World (film)|Spice World]]'') while McCarthy lost to [[Maria Pitillo]] (''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'').<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.razzies.com/forum/1998-razzie-nominees-winners_topic348.html |title= Topic Closed1998 RAZZIE\u00ae Nominees & \"Winners\" |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120831204759/http://www.razzies.com/forum/1998-razzie-nominees-winners_topic348.html |archive-date= 2012-08-31 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn response to a negative review from Roger Ebert, Parker and Stone named the ''South Park'' [[South Park (season 2)|second season]] episode \"[[Roger Ebert Should Lay Off the Fatty Foods]]\", which, despite its title, did not feature Ebert.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chipman |first=Bob |title=15 South Park Episodes That Haven't Aged Well |url=https://screenrant.com/south-park-old-episodes-aged-badly/ |publisher=[[Screen Rant]] |date=May 16, 2017 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Parker and Stone also referenced ''BASEketball''{{'s}} negative reception in ''South Park''{{'s}} [[South Park (season 8)|season eight]] episode, \"[[The Passion of the Jew]]\", where at one point, [[Stan Marsh]] tells [[Kenny McCormick]] as they attempt to get a refund for the tickets they bought to see [[Mel Gibson]]'s ''[[The Passion of the Christ]]'': \"This is about being able to hold bad filmmakers responsible! This is just like when we got our money back for ''BASEketball''!\"\n\n''BASEketball'' is credited with coining the Internet slang term \"[[wikt:derp|derp]]\".<ref name=\"nymag\">{{cite news|last=Becket|first=Stefan|title=The Origins of ''Derp''|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/06/derp-meaning-origin.html|access-date=May 3, 2018|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Siese|first=April|title=These \u2018BASEketball\u2019 Quotes Are Psych-Out Gold|url=https://uproxx.com/movies/baseketball-best-quotes/2/|website=[[Uproxx]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref> Parker and Stone later referenced the term in ''South Park''{{'s}}  [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] episode \"[[The Succubus (South Park)|The Succubus]]\", where [[Chef (South Park)|Chef]] is replaced by [[Mr. Derp]].<ref name=\"nymag\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* \"[[Sarcastaball]]\", an episode of ''[[South Park]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0131857}}\n* {{Amg movie|163059}}\n\n{{Zucker, Abrahams and Zucker}}\n{{Trey Parker and Matt Stone}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baseketball}}\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1990s sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American basketball films]]\n[[Category:American buddy films]]\n[[Category:American sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional ball games]]\n[[Category:Fictional basketball players]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David Zucker (director)]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ira Newborn]]\n[[Category:Films set in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David Zucker (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:American slapstick comedy films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1998 American sports comedy film directed by David Zucker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = BASEketball\n| image = baseketball.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director =  [[David Zucker (director)|David Zucker]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* David Zucker\n* Robert LoCash\n* Gil Netter<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n}}\n| writers =  {{Plainlist|\n* David Zucker\n* Robert LoCash\n* Jeff Wright\n* [[Lewis Friedman]]<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trey Parker]]<!-- Do not list actors that are not included in the poster -->\n* [[Matt Stone]]\n* [[Yasmine Bleeth]]\n* [[Jenny McCarthy]]\n* [[Robert Vaughn]]\n* [[Ernest Borgnine]]\n* [[Dian Bachar]]\n}}\n| music =  [[Ira Newborn|James Ira Newborn]]<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| cinematography =  Steven Mason<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| editing = [[Jeffrey Reiner]]\n| studio =  [[Universal Pictures]]<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| distributor = Universal Pictures<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|title=BASEKetball (1998)|url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/60640?cxt=filmography|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|access-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|1998|07|31}}\n| runtime = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 103:20--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/baseketball-1970-2 | title=''Baseketball'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| country = United States<ref name=\"afi\"/>\n| language = English\n| budget = $23 million\n| gross = $7 million {{small|(U.S. and Canada)}}<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=baseketball.htm|title=BASEketball (1998)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''BASEketball''''' is a 1998 American [[sports comedy]] film co-written and directed by [[David Zucker (director)|David Zucker]] and starring ''[[South Park]]'' creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]], along with [[Yasmine Bleeth]], [[Jenny McCarthy]], [[Robert Vaughn]], [[Ernest Borgnine]], and [[Dian Bachar]]. \n\nThe film follows the history of the sport of the same name (created by Zucker years earlier),{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} from its invention by the lead characters as a game they could win against more [[Sportsperson|athletic]] types, to its development as a nationwide [[Sports league|league]] sport and a target of corporate sponsorship.\n\nThis is the only work involving Parker and Stone that was neither written, directed, nor produced by them, although Zucker himself has stated that Parker and Stone contributed innumerable suggestions for the film, most of which were used.\n\n==Plot==\nLoser best friends Joe \"Coop\" Cooper and Doug Remer [[gate crashing|gate crash]] a high-school reunion and are shunned by their more mature (and successful) classmates. They find themselves outside drinking beer and shooting a basketball when two classmates challenge them to a game. After seeing that their opponents are very good at basketball, they say they will only play a game they picked up in the streets (while secretly inventing the rules as they play, based on both basketball and baseball). After winning, they decide to refine the rules to the game and Coop makes the first BASEketball out of a [[La-Z-Boy]] chair. Their friend, Kenny \"Squeak\" Scolari, tags along and the sport becomes very popular in the neighborhood over the next six months.\n\nBusinessman Ted Denslow meets Coop and Remer and proposes the creation of the National BASEketball League (NBL) along with numerous rules in place to prevent its decline: teams cannot switch cities, players cannot be traded, individuals cannot make money via corporate sponsorship deals, and it is completely open to anyone who wants to play, with Denslow stating that \"anyone can be a sports' hero\". Coop initially hesitates, but quickly accepts the opportunity at hand.\n\nFive years later, the NBL is in full swing with teams, fans, stadiums, and a major championship, the Denslow Cup. Denslow is owner of the Milwaukee Beers, Coop and Remer's team. During the championship game, Denslow dies from choking on a hot dog, causing Coop to miss his shot and costing the Beers the game. Denslow's [[Will and testament|will]] names Coop as owner of the Beers for one year on the condition that they win the next Denslow Cup; otherwise, ownership reverts to Denslow's widow Yvette. Coop declares Remer part owner of the team, and they come to meet Jenna Reed, head of the Dream Come True Foundation, and Joey, one of the children in her care and an avid fan of BASEketball.\n\nBaxter Cain, owner of the Dallas Felons, wants to remove Denslow's rules preventing [[monetization]] of the sport, but could not while Denslow was alive. However, Coop refuses to accept any changes; Cain partners with Yvette as he tries to make the Beers lose the next Denslow Cup so she will own the team.\n\nCain cuts the funding to Jenna's foundation to get Coop and Remer to adopt a clothing line; Coop is against it, but Remer agrees and becomes obsessed with his newfound status. After the semifinals, Cain informs Coop and Remer that the clothing line has been produced through [[child labor]] in [[Calcutta]]; if the public finds out, the team and Jenna's foundation will be ruined. Cain blackmails Coop and Remer into losing or forfeiting the Denslow Cup game or he will inform the public. Jenna learns about the scandal and breaks up with Coop as Coop and Remer blame each other for the predicament.\n\nWith their friendship in shambles, Coop goes to Calcutta, aiming to resolve the situation by replacing the child workers with adults. Making it back to the championship game just as it begins, Coop still blames Remer and the Beers perform abysmally; by the seventh-inning stretch, the Beers are down 16\u20130. Having had enough of Coop and Remer's fighting, Squeak gives the stadium an impassioned speech, reminding Coop and Remer where they came from, how much they changed everyone else's lives, and what they risk losing. Moved, Coop and Remer reconcile their differences as Yvette breaks off her alliance with Cain. After shifting their focus back in the game, they are poised to win when Coop's La-Z-Boy pops. Coop is distraught until Joey brings him a new BASEketball made from a [[Barcalounger]]. After a harrowing last throw, they win the Denslow Cup. Jenna forgives Coop as Yvette makes out with Remer.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Trey Parker]] as Joe \"Coop/Airman\" Cooper\n* [[Matt Stone]] as Doug \"Sir Swish\" Remer\n* [[Dian Bachar]] as Kenny \"Squeak/Little Bitch\" Scolari\n* [[Yasmine Bleeth]] as Jenna Reed\n* [[Jenny McCarthy]] as Yvette Denslow\n* [[Ernest Borgnine]] as Ted Denslow\n* [[Robert Vaughn]] as Baxter Cain\n* [[Trevor Einhorn]] as Joey Thomas\n* [[Francis X. McCarthy]] as Dr. Kaiser (credited as Frank McCarthy) \n* [[Bob Costas]] as Himself\n* [[Al Michaels]] as Himself\n\n[[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Dale Earnhardt]], [[Reggie Jackson]], [[Jim Lampley]], [[Kenny Mayne]], [[Tim McCarver]], [[Pat O'Brien (radio and television personality)|Pat O'Brien]], [[Dan Patrick]], [[Reel Big Fish]], [[Victoria Silvstedt]], and [[Robert Stack]] make cameo appearances as themselves. [[Greg Grunberg]], [[Kevin Michael Richardson]], and [[Peter \"Navy\" Tuiasosopo|Peter Tuiasosopo]] also make cameos as athletes.\n\nZucker had wanted [[Chris Farley]] to play the lead role, before casting Parker and Stone due to their work ''[[South Park]]'' becoming a huge hit. The duo agreed to do the movie under the assumption that their show would have been canceled by the time filming began.<ref>http://www.aintitcool.com/node/1742 </ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack featured a bouncy ska cover of Norwegian band [[a-ha]]'s signature single \"[[Take On Me]]\" by [[Reel Big Fish]]. The band also appears as the live entertainment at the home stadium of the Milwaukee Beers, playing \"Take On Me\" and several of their other songs.<ref>[http://80smusicchannel.blogspot.com/2008/10/ha-take-on-me-1985.html 80s Music Channel: Take On Me]</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 42%, with an average rating of 4.98/10, based on 50 reviews from critics. The website's \"Critics Consensus\" is that the film \"isn't just a succession of fouls thanks to the comedic zip of David Zucker's direction, but sophomoric gags and a lack of performance hustle by Trey Parker and Matt Stone makes this satire a clumsy bunt\".<ref>{{cite web |title=BASEketball (1998) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/baseketball |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a weighted average score of 38 out of 100, based on reviews from 18 critics, indicating \"Generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |title= BASEketball 1998 |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/baseketball |website= [[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade B on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\nIn a positive review with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Leonard Klady said ''BASEketball'' \"has the heightened entertainment challenge of presenting an invented sport ... The film's physical comedy should translate well internationally and chalk up high scores on video\".<ref name=\"klady\">{{cite web |last= Klady |first= Leonard |title=BASEketball |url=https://variety.com/1998/film/reviews/baseketball-1200454253/ |website=Variety |date= July 30, 1998 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> The film was awarded four stars out of five by ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's [[Ian Freer]], who called it funny but described the humor as sometimes hit-and-miss.<ref name=\"freer\">{{cite web |last= Freer |first= Ian |title=BASEketball Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/baseketball/review/ |website=Empire |date=September 8, 2006 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Jack Mathews labeled the film as sleep-inducing and \"by far the most inane and badly written of the comedies made by any of the creators of the classic 1980 sendup ''[[Airplane!]]''\".<ref name=\"jack\">{{cite web |last= Mathews |first= Jack |title=Sophomoric 'BASEketball' Leaves Comedy on the Bench |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jul/31/entertainment/ca-8698 |website=Los Angeles Times |date=July 31, 1998 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Michael O'Sullivan in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' called the film \"dark, dull, witless and hobbled by poor comic timing,\" comparing its gross-out humor unfavorably to that of ''[[There's Something About Mary]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last= O'Sullivan |first= Michael |title='BASEketball' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/movies/reviews/baseketballosullivan.htm?noredirect=on |website=Washington Post |date=July 31, 1998 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] echoed this sentiment in his negative review in the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', giving the film one and a half stars out of four and saying the film \"tries to buy laughs with puerile shocks\".<ref>{{cite web |date=July 31, 1998 |last= Ebert |first= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |title=Baseketball Movie Review & Film Summary (1998) |url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/baseketball-1998 |work= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |accessdate=January 10, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nFor their roles in the film, Yasmine Bleeth and Jenny McCarthy were nominated at the [[1998 Golden Raspberry Awards]], for the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress|Worst Actress]] and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] awards, respectively. Bleeth lost to the [[Spice Girls]] (for ''[[Spice World (film)|Spice World]]'') while McCarthy lost to [[Maria Pitillo]] (''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'').<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.razzies.com/forum/1998-razzie-nominees-winners_topic348.html |title= Topic Closed1998 RAZZIE\u00ae Nominees & \"Winners\" |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120831204759/http://www.razzies.com/forum/1998-razzie-nominees-winners_topic348.html |archive-date= 2012-08-31 }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn response to a negative review from Roger Ebert, Parker and Stone named the ''South Park'' [[South Park (season 2)|second season]] episode \"[[Roger Ebert Should Lay Off the Fatty Foods]]\", which, despite its title, did not feature Ebert.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chipman |first=Bob |title=15 South Park Episodes That Haven't Aged Well |url=https://screenrant.com/south-park-old-episodes-aged-badly/ |publisher=[[Screen Rant]] |date=May 16, 2017 |accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Parker and Stone also referenced ''BASEketball''{{'s}} negative reception in ''South Park''{{'s}} [[South Park (season 8)|season eight]] episode, \"[[The Passion of the Jew]]\", where at one point, [[Stan Marsh]] tells [[Kenny McCormick]] as they attempt to get a refund for the tickets they bought to see [[Mel Gibson]]'s ''[[The Passion of the Christ]]'': \"This is about being able to hold bad filmmakers responsible! This is just like when we got our money back for ''BASEketball''!\"\n\n''BASEketball'' is credited with coining the Internet slang term \"[[wikt:derp|derp]]\".<ref name=\"nymag\">{{cite news|last=Becket|first=Stefan|title=The Origins of ''Derp''|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/06/derp-meaning-origin.html|access-date=May 3, 2018|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=June 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Siese|first=April|title=These \u2018BASEketball\u2019 Quotes Are Psych-Out Gold|url=https://uproxx.com/movies/baseketball-best-quotes/2/|website=[[Uproxx]]|access-date=May 3, 2018|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref> Parker and Stone later referenced the term in ''South Park''{{'s}}  [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] episode \"[[The Succubus (South Park)|The Succubus]]\", where [[Chef (South Park)|Chef]] is replaced by [[Mr. Derp]].<ref name=\"nymag\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* \"[[Sarcastaball]]\", an episode of ''[[South Park]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0131857}}\n* {{Amg movie|163059}}\n\n{{Zucker, Abrahams and Zucker}}\n{{Trey Parker and Matt Stone}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baseketball}}\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1990s sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American basketball films]]\n[[Category:American buddy films]]\n[[Category:American sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional ball games]]\n[[Category:Fictional basketball players]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David Zucker (director)]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ira Newborn]]\n[[Category:Films set in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David Zucker (filmmaker)]]\n[[Category:American slapstick comedy films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BASEketball"}
{"title_page": "Taarka", "text_new": "{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Taarka\n| image_size            = \n| image                 = \n| caption            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Lyons, Colorado|Lyons]], [[Colorado]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]]\n| genre               = [[Folk rock]], [[experimental music|experimental]], [[jazz]]\n| years_active        = 2001&ndash;present\n| label               = [[Frogville Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[ThaMuseMeant]]\n| website                 = [http://www.taarka.com www.taarka.com]\n| current_members     = Enion Pelta&ndash;Tiller<br>David Tiller<br>Dale Largent<br>Troy Robey\n| past_members        = Daniel Plane<br>Jarrod Kaplan<br>James Whiton<br>Damian Erskine<br>Adam Hill}}\n\n'''''Taarka''''' is a [[Lyons, Colorado]]-based musical group originally formed in Portland, Oregon in 2001 by the husband/wife team of David Tiller (mandolin) and Enion Pelta-Tiller (violin). The group originally included Jarrod Kaplan on percussion and James Whiton on stand-up bass. Since their departure Taarka has primarily consisted of a rotating membership. Recent Taarka contributors often include Dale Largent on percussion, Daniel Plane on cello, and Troy Robey on bass.  \n\n==History==\nIn 2000, David Tiller's band, [[ThaMuseMeant]], took a hiatus and Tiller moved to [[New York City]], where he met Enion Pelta through a band called Brooklyn Browngrass. Tiller and Pelta started playing and writing together in early 2001, and the couple soon moved to Oregon. In the coming months, Taarka was formed.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.taarka.com/ | title = Story of Taarka | publisher = taarka.com | date = 2007-10-11 | accessdate = 2007-10-11}}</ref> \n\nIn 2002, ''Taarka: Live In the Studio'' was recorded and released, and although it is currently out of print, it is still available for digital download on [[iTunes]]. In 2003, [[ThaMuseMeant]] re-formed with a new member: Enion Pelta&ndash;Tiller on violin, David Tiller's new wife. In the same year, the Tillers released an acoustic duo album, ''Man Chasing Woman around Table''. On the [[Frogville Records]] website, ''Man Chasing Woman'' is listed as being out of print, but \"maybe available for download soon.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.frogvilleplanet.com/catalog/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=27&products_id=81 | title = Dave & Enion Tiller - Man Chasing - Out Of Print | publisher = [[Frogville Records]] | date = 2007-11-01 | accessdate = 2007-11-01 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110719150448/http://www.frogvilleplanet.com/catalog/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=27&products_id=81 | archivedate = 2011-07-19 | df =  }}</ref> \n\nWith 2004 came two new albums, ThaMuseMeant's ''[[Silver Seed]]'' and Taarka's ''Even Odd Bird''. ''Even Odd Bird'' is the oldest album by Taarka that is currently available for sale on their website. After constant touring for several years, Taarka announced in early 2007 that a new album and EP were to be released that year, titled ''The Trailer'' and ''The Martian Picture Soundtrack''. Both the EP and the album featured renowned bluegrass fiddler [[Darol Anger]] on \"The Creepy,\" a song written by David Tiller, and [[Joe Craven]] (\"Tutu Tango\") and [[Casey Driessen]] (\"Lonely Woman\") were featured on the album.<ref>''The Martian Picture Soundtrack'' liner notes</ref> Beginning on March 18th, 2020 Taarka began hosting live social isolation concerts through Facebook due to the outbreak of the Coronavirus.\n==Etymology==\nTaarka answered how the name \"Taarka\" came about on their website. {{cquote|\"We came up with the name on a spring day in 2002, when Enion, who loves to cook, especially indian food, thought of it: the word which describes roasting spices to create the base for an indian culinary delicacy. There are two kinds of t(a)arkas - wet and dry. A wet t(a)arka is a mix of garlic, ginger and onions sauteed in ghee. A dry t(a)arka is a mixture of whole spices, dry-roasted or fried in oil, til the seeds begin to pop.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.taarka.com/ | title = Often, we're asked, what does TAARKA mean?  | publisher = taarka.com | date = 2007-10-11 | accessdate = 2007-10-11}}</ref>}}\n\n==Band members==\n*David Tiller - Mandolin, Guitars, Vocals, Bass, [[Bouzouki]]\n*Enion Pelta&ndash;Tiller - Violins, Vocals\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"1\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"1\"| Title\n!rowspan=\"1\"| Label\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2001\n|align=\"left\"|''Taarka: Live in the Studio'' \n|align=\"left\"|Omnivine Records\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2003\n|align=\"left\"|''Man Chasing Woman Around Table (Tiller and Pelta duo album)''\n| align=\"left\" |self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2004\n|align=\"left\"|''Even Odd Bird''\n|align=\"left\"|Omnivine Records\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2007\n|align=\"left\"|''The Trailer''\n|align=\"left\"|[[Frogville Records]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2007\n|align=\"left\"|''The Martian Picture Soundtrack''\n|align=\"left\"|Frogville Records\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2008\n|align=\"left\"|''Seed Gathering (EP)''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2009\n|align=\"left\"|''Seed Gathering For A Winter Garden''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2012\n|align=\"left\"|''Adventures in Vagabondia''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2015\n|align=\"left\"|''Making Tracks Home''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2017\n|align=\"left\"|''Fading Mystery''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.taarka.com/ Taarka's official site]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/taarka Facebook]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/taarka Official MySpace]\n* [http://www.frogvilleplanet.com/jamroom/bands/25/ Taarka on Frogville Records]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Musical groups from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2001]]\n[[Category:American folk musical groups]]\n[[Category:American street performers]]\n[[Category:Jam bands]]\n[[Category:American folk rock groups]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Taarka\n| image_size            = \n| image                 = \n| caption            = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Lyons, Colorado|Lyons]], [[Colorado]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]]\n| genre               = [[Folk rock]], [[experimental music|experimental]], [[jazz]]\n| years_active        = 2001&ndash;present\n| label               = [[Frogville Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[ThaMuseMeant]]\n| website                 = [http://www.taarka.com www.taarka.com]\n| current_members     = Enion Pelta&ndash;Tiller<br>David Tiller<br>Dale Largent<br>Troy Robey\n| past_members        = Daniel Plane<br>Jarrod Kaplan<br>James Whiton<br>Damian Erskine<br>Adam Hill}}\n\n'''''Taarka''''' is a [[Lyons, Colorado]]-based musical group originally formed in Portland, Oregon in 2001 by the husband/wife team of David Tiller (mandolin) and Enion Pelta-Tiller (violin). The group originally included Jarrod Kaplan on percussion and James Whiton on stand-up bass. Since their departure Taarka has primarily consisted of a rotating membership. Recent Taarka contributors often include Dale Largent on percussion, Daniel Plane on cello, and Troy Robey on bass.  \n\n==History==\nIn 2000, David Tiller's band, [[ThaMuseMeant]], took a hiatus and Tiller moved to [[New York City]], where he met Enion Pelta through a band called Brooklyn Browngrass. Tiller and Pelta started playing and writing together in early 2001, and the couple soon moved to Oregon. In the coming months, Taarka was formed.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.taarka.com/ | title = Story of Taarka | publisher = taarka.com | date = 2007-10-11 | accessdate = 2007-10-11}}</ref> \n\nIn 2002, ''Taarka: Live In the Studio'' was recorded and released, and although it is currently out of print, it is still available for digital download on [[iTunes]]. In 2003, [[ThaMuseMeant]] re-formed with a new member: Enion Pelta&ndash;Tiller on violin, David Tiller's new wife. In the same year, the Tillers released an acoustic duo album, ''Man Chasing Woman around Table''. On the [[Frogville Records]] website, ''Man Chasing Woman'' is listed as being out of print, but \"maybe available for download soon.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.frogvilleplanet.com/catalog/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=27&products_id=81 | title = Dave & Enion Tiller - Man Chasing - Out Of Print | publisher = [[Frogville Records]] | date = 2007-11-01 | accessdate = 2007-11-01 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110719150448/http://www.frogvilleplanet.com/catalog/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=27&products_id=81 | archivedate = 2011-07-19 | df =  }}</ref> \n\nWith 2004 came two new albums, ThaMuseMeant's ''[[Silver Seed]]'' and Taarka's ''Even Odd Bird''. ''Even Odd Bird'' is the oldest album by Taarka that is currently available for sale on their website. After constant touring for several years, Taarka announced in early 2007 that a new album and EP were to be released that year, titled ''The Trailer'' and ''The Martian Picture Soundtrack''. Both the EP and the album featured renowned bluegrass fiddler [[Darol Anger]] on \"The Creepy,\" a song written by David Tiller, and [[Joe Craven]] (\"Tutu Tango\") and [[Casey Driessen]] (\"Lonely Woman\") were featured on the album.<ref>''The Martian Picture Soundtrack'' liner notes</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nTaarka answered how the name \"Taarka\" came about on their website. {{cquote|\"We came up with the name on a spring day in 2002, when Enion, who loves to cook, especially indian food, thought of it: the word which describes roasting spices to create the base for an indian culinary delicacy. There are two kinds of t(a)arkas - wet and dry. A wet t(a)arka is a mix of garlic, ginger and onions sauteed in ghee. A dry t(a)arka is a mixture of whole spices, dry-roasted or fried in oil, til the seeds begin to pop.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.taarka.com/ | title = Often, we're asked, what does TAARKA mean?  | publisher = taarka.com | date = 2007-10-11 | accessdate = 2007-10-11}}</ref>}}\n\n==Band members==\n*David Tiller - Mandolin, Guitars, Vocals, Bass, [[Bouzouki]]\n*Enion Pelta&ndash;Tiller - Violins, Vocals\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"1\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"1\"| Title\n!rowspan=\"1\"| Label\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2001\n|align=\"left\"|''Taarka: Live in the Studio'' \n|align=\"left\"|Omnivine Records\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2003\n|align=\"left\"|''Man Chasing Woman Around Table (Tiller and Pelta duo album)''\n| align=\"left\" |self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2004\n|align=\"left\"|''Even Odd Bird''\n|align=\"left\"|Omnivine Records\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2007\n|align=\"left\"|''The Trailer''\n|align=\"left\"|[[Frogville Records]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2007\n|align=\"left\"|''The Martian Picture Soundtrack''\n|align=\"left\"|Frogville Records\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2008\n|align=\"left\"|''Seed Gathering (EP)''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2009\n|align=\"left\"|''Seed Gathering For A Winter Garden''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2012\n|align=\"left\"|''Adventures in Vagabondia''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2015\n|align=\"left\"|''Making Tracks Home''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2017\n|align=\"left\"|''Fading Mystery''\n|align=\"left\"|self-released\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.taarka.com/ Taarka's official site]\n* [http://www.