e)\n* [http://web.archive.org/web/20081112224705/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com/uk/available.html List of every Game by 12th November 2008]\n* [http://web.archive.org/web/20081112150551/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com/uk/release.html List of planned games by 12th November 2008]\n* [http://phoenixgamesltd.com/ unofficial Website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/PhoenixGamesBV/ Facebook]\n\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Video game publishers]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n", "name_user": "DJ Kaito", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePSP (unreleased)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenix_Games_B.V."}
{"title_page": "Ogura Hyakunin Isshu", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n[[Image:Hyakuninisshu 001.jpg|thumb|First poem card of the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', featuring [[Emperor Tenji]]]]\n[[Image:Ogura Shikishi.jpg|thumb|Ogura ''{{wt|ja|\u8272\u7d19|shikishi}}'' by Teika]]\n{{nihongo|'''''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'''''|\u5c0f\u5009\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}} is a classical Japanese anthology of one hundred Japanese [[Waka (poetry)|''waka'']] by one hundred poets. ''Hyakunin isshu'' can be translated to \"one hundred people, one poem [each]\"; it can also refer to the card game of ''[[uta-garuta]]'', which uses a deck composed of cards based on the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''.\n\nIt was compiled by [[Fujiwara no Teika]] while he lived in the [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Ogura district]] of [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]].<ref>Mostow, Joshua. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA25&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image,'' p.25.]</ref>\n\n==Compilation==\nOne of Teika's diaries, the ''Meigetsuki'', says that his son [[Fujiwara no Tameie|Tameie]] asked him to arrange one hundred poems for Tameie's father-in-law, [[Utsunomiya Yoritsuna]], who was furnishing a residence near [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Mount Ogura]];<ref>Ogurayama: Latitude: 34\u00b0 53' 60 N, Longitude: 135\u00b0 46' 60 E; Kyoto Prefecture web site: [http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search  northwest of Arashiyama Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112301/http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search |date=2011-07-22 }}.</ref> hence the full name of ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''. In order to decorate screens of the residence, [[Fujiwara no Teika]] produced the calligraphy poem sheets.<ref>Mostow, [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA94&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  p.94.]</ref>\n\n[[Hishikawa Moronobu]] provided woodblock portraits for each of the poets included in the anthology.<ref name=\"wdl2929\">{{cite web|title=100 Poems by 100 Poets|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/2929/|website=[[World Digital Library]]|date=1680|accessdate=7 June 2013|language=Japanese|author1=Hishikawa, Moronobu\n|author2=Fujiwara, Sadaie}}</ref>\n\nIn his own lifetime, Teika was better known for other work.  For example, in 1200 (''Sh\u014dji 2''), Teika prepared another anthology of one hundred poems for ex-[[Emperor Go-Toba]]. This was called the ''Sh\u014dji Hyakushu''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brower|first=Robert H.|title=Fujiwara Teika's Hundred-Poem Sequence of the Sh\u014dji Era|jstor=2384210|journal=[[Monumenta Nipponica]]|volume=31|issue=3|date=Autumn 1976|pages=223\u2013249|doi=10.2307/2384210}}</ref>\n\n==Poets==\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor Tenji]]|\u5929\u667a\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Empress Jit\u014d]]|\u6301\u7d71\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]]|\u67ff\u672c\u4eba\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Yamabe no Akahito]]|\u5c71\u90e8\u8d64\u4eba}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sarumaru Day\u016b]]|\u733f\u4e38\u5927\u592b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ch\u016bnagon|Middle Counselor]] [[\u014ctomo no Yakamochi|Yakamochi]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5bb6\u6301}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Abe no Nakamaro]]|\u963f\u500d\u4ef2\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Kisen]]|\u559c\u64b0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ono no Komachi]]|\u5c0f\u91ce\u5c0f\u753a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Semimaru]]|\u8749\u4e38}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Ono no Takamura|Takamura]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7bc1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[High priest|High Priest]] [[Henj\u014d]]|\u50e7\u6b63\u904d\u662d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Y\u014dzei]]|\u967d\u6210\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no T\u014dru|Minister of the Left of Kawara]]|\u6cb3\u539f\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor K\u014dk\u014d]]|\u5149\u5b5d\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Counselor [[Ariwara no Yukihira|Yukihira]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u884c\u5e73}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ariwara no Narihira]] ''[[Ason]]''|\u5728\u539f\u696d\u5e73\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Toshiyuki]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u654f\u884c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Lady Ise|Ise]]|\u4f0a\u52e2}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Prince Motoyoshi]]|\u5143\u826f\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Sosei]]|\u7d20\u6027\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Yasuhide]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u5eb7\u79c0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014ce no Chisato]]|\u5927\u6c5f\u5343\u91cc}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sugawara no Michizane|Kanke]]|\u83c5\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sadakata|Minister of the Right of Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadahira|Teishin-k\u014d]]|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Counselor [[Fujiwara no Kanesuke|Kanesuke]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u517c\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Muneyuki]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u5b97\u4e8e\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cshik\u014dchi no Mitsune]]|\u51e1\u6cb3\u5185\u8eac\u6052}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadamine]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u5c91}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sakanoue no Korenori]]|\u5742\u4e0a\u662f\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Harumichi no Tsuraki]]|\u6625\u9053\u5217\u6a39}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tomonori]]|\u7d00\u53cb\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Okikaze]]|\u85e4\u539f\u8208\u98a8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tsurayuki]]|\u7d00\u8cab\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Fukayabu]]|\u6e05\u539f\u6df1\u990a\u7236}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Asayasu]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u671d\u5eb7}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ukon (poet)|Ukon]]|\u53f3\u8fd1}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Minamoto no Hitoshi|Hitoshi]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7b49}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taira no Kanemori]]|\u5e73\u517c\u76db}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadami]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u898b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Motosuke]]|\u6e05\u539f\u5143\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Counselor [[Fujiwara no Atsutada|Atsutada]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u6566\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Counselor [[Fujiwara no Asatada|Asatada]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u671d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Koretada|Kentoku-k\u014d]]|\u8b19\u5fb3\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sone no Yoshitada]]|\u66fd\u79b0\u597d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Egy\u014d]]|\u6075\u6176\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Shigeyuki]]|\u6e90\u91cd\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cnakatomi no Yoshinobu]] ''Ason''|\u5927\u4e2d\u81e3\u80fd\u5ba3\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Yoshitaka]]|\u85e4\u539f\u7fa9\u5b5d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sanekata]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u5b9f\u65b9\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Michinobu]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u9053\u4fe1\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Michitsuna no Haha|Mother of the Right Captain Michitsuna]]|\u53f3\u5927\u5c06\u9053\u7db1\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Takashina no Takako|Mother of the Honorary Grand Minister]]|\u5100\u540c\u4e09\u53f8\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Dainagon|Upper Counselor]] [[Fujiwara no Kint\u014d|Kint\u014d]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u516c\u4efb}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Izumi Shikibu]]|\u548c\u6cc9\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Murasaki Shikibu]]|\u7d2b\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Daini no Sanmi]]|\u5927\u5f10\u4e09\u4f4d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Akazome Emon]]|\u8d64\u67d3\u885b\u9580}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Koshikibu no Naishi]]|\u5c0f\u5f0f\u90e8\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ise no Taifu]]|\u4f0a\u52e2\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sei Sh\u014dnagon]]|\u6e05\u5c11\u7d0d\u8a00}}\n# {{nihongo|Master of the Left Capital [[Fujiwara no Michimasa|Michimasa]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9053\u96c5}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Counselor [[Fujiwara no Sadayori|Sadayori]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u983c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sagami (poet)|Sagami]]|\u76f8\u6a21}}\n# {{nihongo|Senior High Priest [[Gy\u014dson]]|\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u884c\u5c0a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Su\u014d no Naishi]]|\u5468\u9632\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[N\u014din]]|\u80fd\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Ry\u014dzen]]|\u826f\u66b9\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Upper Counselor [[Minamoto no Tsunenobu|Tsunenobu]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u7d4c\u4fe1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Y\u016bshi Naishinn\u014d-ke no Kii|Kii of Princess Y\u016bshi's Household]]|\u7950\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b\u5bb6\u7d00\u4f0a}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Counselor [[\u014ce no Masafusa|Masafusa]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5321\u623f}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Toshiyori]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u4fca\u983c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Mototoshi]]|\u85e4\u539f\u57fa\u4fca}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadamichi|Lay Novice of Hossh\u014d-ji Temple, former ''Kampaku'' and Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u6cd5\u6027\u5bfa\u5165\u9053\u524d\u95a2\u767d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sutoku]]|\u5d07\u5fb3\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Kanemasa]]|\u6e90\u517c\u660c}}\n# {{nihongo|Master of the Left Capital [[Fujiwara no Akisuke|Akisuke]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9855\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taikenmon'in no Horikawa|Horikawa, attendant to Empress Taiken]]|\u5f85\u8ce2\u9580\u9662\u5800\u6cb3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Tokudaiji Sanesada|Later Tokudaiji Minister of the Left]]|\u5f8c\u5fb3\u5927\u5bfa\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[D\u014din]]|\u9053\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Master of the Empress Dowager's Household [[Fujiwara no Shunzei|Shunzei/Toshinari]]|\u7687\u592a\u540e\u5bae\u5927\u592b\u4fca\u6210}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Kiyosuke]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u6e05\u8f14\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Shun'e]]|\u4fca\u6075\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Saigy\u014d]]|\u897f\u884c\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Jakuren]]|\u5bc2\u84ee\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[K\u014dkamonin no Bett\u014d|Attendant to Empress K\u014dka]]|\u7687\u5609\u9580\u9662\u5225\u5f53}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Princess Shikishi]]|\u5f0f\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Inpumon'in no Tay\u016b|Attendant to Empress Inpu]]|\u6bb7\u5bcc\u9580\u9662\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kuj\u014d Yoshitsune|Goky\u014dgoku Regent and former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5f8c\u4eac\u6975\u6442\u653f\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Nij\u014din no Sanuki|Sanuki, attendant to retired Emperor Nij\u014d]]|\u4e8c\u6761\u9662\u8b83\u5c90}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Sanetomo|Minister of the Right of Kamakura]]|\u938c\u5009\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Asukai no Masatsune|Masatsune]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u96c5\u7d4c}}\n# {{nihongo|Former Senior High Priest [[Jien]]|\u524d\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u6148\u5186}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Saionji Kintsune|Lay Novice and former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5165\u9053\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Counselor [[Fujiwara no Teika|Teika/Sadaie]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ritsury\u014d#Establishment of court rank|Junior Second Rank]] [[Fujiwara no Ietaka|Ietaka]]|\u5f93\u4e8c\u4f4d\u5bb6\u9686}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Go-Toba]]|\u5f8c\u9ce5\u7fbd\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Juntoku]]|\u9806\u5fb3\u9662}}\n\n==Poems==\n[[File:Hyakunin Isshu.JPG|thumb|right|250px|An [[Edo period|Edo-period]] illustrated ''Hyakunin Isshu'' book, with Priest Kisen and Ono no Komachi.]]\n\n===Poem number 2===\nA visually-descriptive poem attributed to [[Empress Jit\u014d]]. Teika chose this poem from the ''[[Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b]]'':\n\n{{waka\n|\u6625\u904e\u304e\u3066\u590f\u6765\u306b\u3051\u3089\u3057{{wt|ja|\u767d\u5999\u306e}}|\u8863\u5e72\u3059\u3066\u3075\u5929\u306e\u9999\u5177\u5c71\n|reading = haru sugite natsu kinikerashi shirotae no<br/>koromo hosu ch\u014d Ama no Kaguyama\n|translation = Spring has passed, and the white robes of summer are being aired on fragrant Mount Kagu\u2014beloved of the gods.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Teika|translator-last1=MacMillan|translator-first1=Peter|date=2018|title=One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9780141395944}}</ref>\n|source = ''Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b'' 3:175\n}}\n\nThe original was likely based from a poem of the ''[[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b]]'' (book 1, poem 28) by the same poet.\n\n===Poem number 26===\nA quite different poem is attributed to ''[[Minister of the Left|Sadaijin]]'' [[Fujiwara no Tadahira]] in the context of a very specific incident.  After abdicating, former [[Emperor Uda]] visited Mount Ogura in [[Yamashiro Province]]. He was so greatly impressed by the beauty of autumn colours of the maples that he ordered Fujiwara no Tadahira to encourage Uda's son and heir, [[Emperor Daigo]], to visit the same area.\n\n{{nihongo|Prince Tenshin or Teishin|{{wt|ja|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}|''Teishin-k\u014d''}} was Tadahira's posthumous name, and this is the name used in William Porter's translation of the poem which observes that \"[t]he maples of Mount Ogura / If they could understand / Would keep their brilliant leaves / until [t]he Ruler of this land / Pass with his Royal band.\"  The accompanying 18th century illustration shows a person of consequence riding an ox in a procession with attendants on foot.  The group is passing through an area of maple leaves.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Sadaie|translator-last1=Porter|translator-first1=William N.|date=2007|title=A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the ''Hyakunin Isshu''|edition=illustrated, reprint|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&pg=PA26&dq=hyakunin+ogura#PPA26,M1|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9784805308530|pages=25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nTeika chose this poem from the ''[[Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b]]'' for the hundred poems collection:\n\n{{waka|\u5c0f\u5009\u5c71\u5cf0\u306e\u3082\u307f\u3062\u8449\u5fc3\u3042\u3089\u3070|\u4eca\u3072\u3068\u305f\u3073\u306e\u884c\u5e78\u307e\u305f\u306a\u3080|reading = Ogura-yama mine no momijiba kokoro araba<br/>ima hitotabi no miyuki matanan<ref>The modern romanization of the last line would be ''miyuki '''matanamu''''' (\u201cawait the emperor's pilgrimage\u201d); by applying the [[historical kana orthography]], ''matanamu'' would be pronounced ''matana'''n'''''.</ref>|translation = Maple leaves on Ogura mountain: if you had a heart, I would have you wait for one more royal visit!<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kamens|first1=Edward|last2=Kamens|first2=Howard I.|date=1997|title=Utamakura, Allusion, and Intertextuality in Traditional Japanese Poetry|edition=illustrated|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300068085|page=102}}</ref>|source = ''Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b'' 17:1128}}\n\n==English translations==\nThe ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'' has been translated into many languages and into English many times, beginning with [[Yone Noguchi]]'s ''Hyaku Nin Isshu in English'' in 1907.<ref>Yone Noguchi, [http://www.h.ehime-u.ac.jp/-marx/YN/articles/hyakunin.htm Hyaku Nin Isshu in English, ''Waseda Bungaku'' (1907)]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOther translations include:\n* William N. Porter, ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan'' (1909)\n* Clay MacCauley, ''Hyakunin-isshu (Single Songs of a Hundred Poets)'' (1917)\n* Tom Galt, ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each'' (1982)\n* Joshua S. Mostow, ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image'' (1996)\n* Peter MacMillan, ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'' (2008; [[Penguin Classics]], revised edition 2018)\n* Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'' (2008)\n\n==Other Hyakunin Isshu anthologies==\nMany other anthologies compiled along the same criteria\u2014one hundred poems by one hundred poets\u2014include the words ''hyakunin isshu'', notably the [[World War II]]-era {{nihongo|''Aikoku Hyakunin Isshu''|\u611b\u56fd\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, or ''One Hundred Patriotic Poems by One Hundred Poets''. Also important is {{nihongo|''Ky\u014dka Hyakunin Isshu''|\u72c2\u6b4c\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, a series of parodies of the original ''Ogura'' collection.\n\n==Card game==\nTeika's anthology is the basis for the card game of ''[[karuta]]'', which has been popular since the [[Edo period]].<ref>[[William H. Honan|Honan, William H.]] [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/06/books/why-millions-in-japan-read-all-about-poetry.html?scp=26&sq=Donald+Keene&st=nyt  \"Why Millions in Japan Read All About Poetry,\"] ''New York Times.'' March 6, 2000.</ref>\n\nMany forms of playing games with ''Hyakunin Isshu'' exist in Japan, such as ''[[Uta-garuta]]'', the basis for [[competitive karuta]] (''ky\u014dgi karuta'').\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nisonin]], Kyoto\n* [[Shigureden]], a museum in Kyoto about this subject\n\n==References==\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Thomas Galt. (1982). [https://books.google.com/books?id=4yuXGwAACAAJ&dq=The+Little+Treasury+of+One+Hundred+People,+One+Poem+Each&client=firefox-a  ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each.''] Princeton: [[Princeton University Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-691-06514-4}}\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Yoritsuna Utsunomiya, William Ninnis Porter. (1979) [https://books.google.com/books?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&client=firefox-a  ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu: Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu.''] Tokyo: [[Tuttle Publishing]]. {{ISBN|978-4-8053-0853-0}}\n* Mostow, Joshua S., ed. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Pictures+of+the+Heart:+The+Hyakunin+Isshu+in+Word+and+Image.&client=firefox-a  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image.''] Honolulu: [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-8248-1705-3}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/pictures-of-the-heart-the-hyakunin-isshu-in-word-and-image/oclc/645187818 OCLC 645187818]\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Translation of the Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', Peter McMillan, foreword by Donald Keene. New York: Columbia University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-231-14398-1}} <!-- http://cup.columbia.edu/book/978-0-231-14398-1/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each -->\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'', Peter McMillan. London: Penguin Classics, 2018. {{ISBN|9780141395937}} <!-- https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/269418/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each/ -->\n* ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'', Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, translators. Tokyo: PIE Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-4-89444-757-8}} <!-- http://www.piebooks.com/search/detail.php?ID=1108 -->  This book is also available as an iPad/iPhone application.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Hyakunin Isshu}}\n{{Wikisource|Ogura Hyakunin Isshu|''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''}}\n*[http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/hyakunin/index.html ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu - 100 Poems by 100 Poets''] at [[University of Virginia]] Library Japanese Text Initiative\n* {{librivox book | dtitle=Ogura Hyakunin Isshu | stitle=o | | author=Teika no FUJIWARA}}\n\n{{Japanese poetry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese literature]]\n[[Category:Japanese poetry anthologies]]\n[[Category:Articles containing Japanese poems]]\n[[Category:Fujiwara no Teika]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n[[Image:Hyakuninisshu 001.jpg|thumb|First poem card of the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', featuring [[Emperor Tenji]]]]\n[[Image:Ogura Shikishi.jpg|thumb|Ogura ''{{wt|ja|\u8272\u7d19|shikishi}}'' by Teika]]\n{{nihongo|'''''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'''''|\u5c0f\u5009\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}} is a classical Japanese anthology of one hundred Japanese [[Waka (poetry)|''waka'']] by one hundred poets. ''Hyakunin isshu'' can be translated to \"one hundred people, one poem [each]\"; it can also refer to the card game of ''[[uta-garuta]]'', which uses a deck composed of cards based on the ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''.\n\nIt was compiled by [[Fujiwara no Teika]] while he lived in the [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Ogura district]] of [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]].<ref>Mostow, Joshua. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA25&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image,'' p.25.]</ref>\n\n==Compilation==\nOne of Teika's diaries, the ''Meigetsuki'', says that his son [[Fujiwara no Tameie|Tameie]] asked him to arrange one hundred poems for Tameie's father-in-law, [[Utsunomiya Yoritsuna]], who was furnishing a residence near [[Uky\u014d-ku, Kyoto|Mount Ogura]];<ref>Ogurayama: Latitude: 34\u00b0 53' 60 N, Longitude: 135\u00b0 46' 60 E; Kyoto Prefecture web site: [http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search  northwest of Arashiyama Park] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112301/http://www2.pref.kyoto.lg.jp/cgi-bin/en/namazu.cgi?key=ogura&max=30&format=long&whence=0&submit=Search |date=2011-07-22 }}.</ref> hence the full name of ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''. In order to decorate screens of the residence, [[Fujiwara no Teika]] produced the calligraphy poem sheets.<ref>Mostow, [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&pg=PA94&dq=Hyakunin+Isshu+ogura+villa&lr=  p.94.]</ref>\n\n[[Hishikawa Moronobu]] provided woodblock portraits for each of the poets included in the anthology.<ref name=\"wdl2929\">{{cite web|title=100 Poems by 100 Poets|url=http://www.wdl.org/en/item/2929/|website=[[World Digital Library]]|date=1680|accessdate=7 June 2013|language=Japanese|author1=Hishikawa, Moronobu\n|author2=Fujiwara, Sadaie}}</ref>\n\nIn his own lifetime, Teika was better known for other work.  For example, in 1200 (''Sh\u014dji 2''), Teika prepared another anthology of one hundred poems for ex-[[Emperor Go-Toba]]. This was called the ''Sh\u014dji Hyakushu''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brower|first=Robert H.|title=Fujiwara Teika's Hundred-Poem Sequence of the Sh\u014dji Era|jstor=2384210|journal=[[Monumenta Nipponica]]|volume=31|issue=3|date=Autumn 1976|pages=223\u2013249|doi=10.2307/2384210}}</ref>\n\n==Poets==\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor Tenji]]|\u5929\u667a\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Empress Jit\u014d]]|\u6301\u7d71\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kakinomoto no Hitomaro]]|\u67ff\u672c\u4eba\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Yamabe no Akahito]]|\u5c71\u90e8\u8d64\u4eba}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sarumaru Day\u016b]]|\u733f\u4e38\u5927\u592b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ch\u016bnagon|Middle Councillor]] [[\u014ctomo no Yakamochi|Yakamochi]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5bb6\u6301}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Abe no Nakamaro]]|\u963f\u500d\u4ef2\u9ebb\u5442}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Kisen]]|\u559c\u64b0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ono no Komachi]]|\u5c0f\u91ce\u5c0f\u753a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Semimaru]]|\u8749\u4e38}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Ono no Takamura|Takamura]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7bc1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[High priest|High Priest]] [[Henj\u014d]]|\u50e7\u6b63\u904d\u662d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Y\u014dzei]]|\u967d\u6210\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no T\u014dru|Minister of the Left of Kawara]]|\u6cb3\u539f\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Emperor K\u014dk\u014d]]|\u5149\u5b5d\u5929\u7687}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Ariwara no Yukihira|Yukihira]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u884c\u5e73}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ariwara no Narihira]] ''[[Ason]]''|\u5728\u539f\u696d\u5e73\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Toshiyuki]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u654f\u884c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Lady Ise|Ise]]|\u4f0a\u52e2}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Prince Motoyoshi]]|\u5143\u826f\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Sosei]]|\u7d20\u6027\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Yasuhide]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u5eb7\u79c0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014ce no Chisato]]|\u5927\u6c5f\u5343\u91cc}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sugawara no Michizane|Kanke]]|\u83c5\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sadakata|Minister of the Right of Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadahira|Teishin-k\u014d]]|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Kanesuke|Kanesuke]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u517c\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Muneyuki]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u5b97\u4e8e\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cshik\u014dchi no Mitsune]]|\u51e1\u6cb3\u5185\u8eac\u6052}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadamine]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u5c91}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sakanoue no Korenori]]|\u5742\u4e0a\u662f\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Harumichi no Tsuraki]]|\u6625\u9053\u5217\u6a39}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tomonori]]|\u7d00\u53cb\u5247}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Okikaze]]|\u85e4\u539f\u8208\u98a8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ki no Tsurayuki]]|\u7d00\u8cab\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Fukayabu]]|\u6e05\u539f\u6df1\u990a\u7236}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fun'ya no Asayasu]]|\u6587\u5c4b\u671d\u5eb7}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ukon (poet)|Ukon]]|\u53f3\u8fd1}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Minamoto no Hitoshi|Hitoshi]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u7b49}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taira no Kanemori]]|\u5e73\u517c\u76db}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Mibu no Tadami]]|\u58ec\u751f\u5fe0\u898b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kiyohara no Motosuke]]|\u6e05\u539f\u5143\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Atsutada|Atsutada]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u6566\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Asatada|Asatada]]|\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u671d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Koretada|Kentoku-k\u014d]]|\u8b19\u5fb3\u516c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sone no Yoshitada]]|\u66fd\u79b0\u597d\u5fe0}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Egy\u014d]]|\u6075\u6176\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Shigeyuki]]|\u6e90\u91cd\u4e4b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[\u014cnakatomi no Yoshinobu]] ''Ason''|\u5927\u4e2d\u81e3\u80fd\u5ba3\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Yoshitaka]]|\u85e4\u539f\u7fa9\u5b5d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Sanekata]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u5b9f\u65b9\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Michinobu]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u9053\u4fe1\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Michitsuna no Haha|Mother of the Right Captain Michitsuna]]|\u53f3\u5927\u5c06\u9053\u7db1\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Takashina no Takako|Mother of the Honorary Grand Minister]]|\u5100\u540c\u4e09\u53f8\u6bcd}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Dainagon|Upper Councillor]] [[Fujiwara no Kint\u014d|Kint\u014d]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u516c\u4efb}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Izumi Shikibu]]|\u548c\u6cc9\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Murasaki Shikibu]]|\u7d2b\u5f0f\u90e8}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Daini no Sanmi]]|\u5927\u5f10\u4e09\u4f4d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Akazome Emon]]|\u8d64\u67d3\u885b\u9580}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Koshikibu no Naishi]]|\u5c0f\u5f0f\u90e8\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Ise no Taifu]]|\u4f0a\u52e2\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sei Sh\u014dnagon]]|\u6e05\u5c11\u7d0d\u8a00}}\n# {{nihongo|Chief Magistrate of the Left [[Fujiwara no Michimasa|Michimasa]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9053\u96c5}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Sadayori|Sadayori]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u983c}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Sagami (poet)|Sagami]]|\u76f8\u6a21}}\n# {{nihongo|Archbishop [[Gy\u014dson]]|\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u884c\u5c0a}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Su\u014d no Naishi]]|\u5468\u9632\u5185\u4f8d}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sanj\u014d]]|\u4e09\u6761\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[N\u014din]]|\u80fd\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Ry\u014dzen]]|\u826f\u66b9\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Upper Councillor [[Minamoto no Tsunenobu|Tsunenobu]]|\u5927\u7d0d\u8a00\u7d4c\u4fe1}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Y\u016bshi Naishinn\u014d-ke no Kii|Kii of Princess Y\u016bshi's Household]]|\u7950\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b\u5bb6\u7d00\u4f0a}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[\u014ce no Masafusa|Masafusa]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5321\u623f}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Toshiyori]] ''Ason''|\u6e90\u4fca\u983c\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Mototoshi]]|\u85e4\u539f\u57fa\u4fca}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Tadamichi|Lay Priest of Hossh\u014d-ji Temple, former ''Kampaku'' and Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u6cd5\u6027\u5bfa\u5165\u9053\u524d\u95a2\u767d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Sutoku]]|\u5d07\u5fb3\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Kanemasa]]|\u6e90\u517c\u660c}}\n# {{nihongo|Chief Magistrate of the Left [[Fujiwara no Akisuke|Akisuke]]|\u5de6\u4eac\u5927\u592b\u9855\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Taikenmon'in no Horikawa|Horikawa, attendant to Empress Taiken]]|\u5f85\u8ce2\u9580\u9662\u5800\u6cb3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Tokudaiji Sanesada|Later Tokudaiji Minister of the Left]]|\u5f8c\u5fb3\u5927\u5bfa\u5de6\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[D\u014din]]|\u9053\u56e0\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Master of the Empress Dowager's Household [[Fujiwara no Shunzei|Shunzei/Toshinari]]|\u7687\u592a\u540e\u5bae\u5927\u592b\u4fca\u6210}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Fujiwara no Kiyosuke]] ''Ason''|\u85e4\u539f\u6e05\u8f14\u671d\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Shun'e]]|\u4fca\u6075\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Saigy\u014d]]|\u897f\u884c\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|Priest [[Jakuren]]|\u5bc2\u84ee\u6cd5\u5e2b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[K\u014dkamonin no Bett\u014d|Attendant to Empress K\u014dka]]|\u7687\u5609\u9580\u9662\u5225\u5f53}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Princess Shikishi]]|\u5f0f\u5b50\u5185\u89aa\u738b}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Inpumon'in no Tay\u016b|Attendant to Empress Inpu]]|\u6bb7\u5bcc\u9580\u9662\u5927\u8f14}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Kuj\u014d Yoshitsune|Goky\u014dgoku Regent and Former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5f8c\u4eac\u6975\u6442\u653f\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Nij\u014din no Sanuki|Sanuki, attendant to retired Emperor Nij\u014d]]|\u4e8c\u6761\u9662\u8b83\u5c90}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Minamoto no Sanetomo|Minister of the Right of Kamakura]]|\u938c\u5009\u53f3\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Councillor [[Asukai no Masatsune|Masatsune]]|\u53c2\u8b70\u96c5\u7d4c}}\n# {{nihongo|Former Archbishop [[Jien]]|\u524d\u5927\u50e7\u6b63\u6148\u5186}}\n# {{nihongo|[[Saionji Kintsune|Lay Priest and Former Chancellor of the Realm]]|\u5165\u9053\u524d\u592a\u653f\u5927\u81e3}}\n# {{nihongo|Acting Middle Councillor [[Fujiwara no Teika|Teika/Sadaie]]|\u6a29\u4e2d\u7d0d\u8a00\u5b9a\u5bb6}}\n# {{nihongo|Junior Second Rank [[Fujiwara no Ietaka|Ietaka]]|\u5f93\u4e8c\u4f4d\u5bb6\u9686}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Go-Toba]]|\u5f8c\u9ce5\u7fbd\u9662}}\n# {{nihongo|Retired [[Emperor Juntoku]]|\u9806\u5fb3\u9662}}\n\n==Poems==\n[[File:Hyakunin Isshu.JPG|thumb|right|250px|An [[Edo period|Edo-period]] illustrated ''Hyakunin Isshu'' book, with Priest Kisen and Ono no Komachi.]]\n\n===Poem number 2===\nA visually-descriptive poem attributed to [[Empress Jit\u014d]]. Teika chose this poem from the ''[[Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b]]'':\n\n{{waka\n|\u6625\u904e\u304e\u3066\u590f\u6765\u306b\u3051\u3089\u3057{{wt|ja|\u767d\u5999\u306e}}|\u8863\u5e72\u3059\u3066\u3075\u5929\u306e\u9999\u5177\u5c71\n|reading = haru sugite natsu kinikerashi shirotae no<br/>koromo hosu ch\u014d Ama no Kaguyama\n|translation = Spring has passed, and the white robes of summer are being aired on fragrant Mount Kagu\u2014beloved of the gods.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Teika|translator-last1=MacMillan|translator-first1=Peter|date=2018|title=One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse|publisher=Penguin UK|isbn=9780141395944}}</ref>\n|source = ''Shin Kokin Wakash\u016b'' 3:175\n}}\n\nThe original was likely based from a poem of the ''[[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b]]'' (book 1, poem 28) by the same poet.\n\n===Poem number 26===\nA quite different poem is attributed to ''[[Minister of the Left|Sadaijin]]'' [[Fujiwara no Tadahira]] in the context of a very specific incident.  After abdicating, former [[Emperor Uda]] visited Mount Ogura in [[Yamashiro Province]]. He was so greatly impressed by the beauty of autumn colours of the maples that he ordered Fujiwara no Tadahira to encourage Uda's son and heir, [[Emperor Daigo]], to visit the same area.\n\n{{nihongo|Prince Tenshin or Teishin|{{wt|ja|\u8c9e\u4fe1\u516c}}|''Teishin-k\u014d''}} was Tadahira's posthumous name, and this is the name used in William Porter's translation of the poem which observes that \"[t]he maples of Mount Ogura / If they could understand / Would keep their brilliant leaves / until [t]he Ruler of this land / Pass with his Royal band.\"  The accompanying 18th century illustration shows a person of consequence riding an ox in a procession with attendants on foot.  The group is passing through an area of maple leaves.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujiwara|first=Sadaie|translator-last1=Porter|translator-first1=William N.|date=2007|title=A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the ''Hyakunin Isshu''|edition=illustrated, reprint|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&pg=PA26&dq=hyakunin+ogura#PPA26,M1|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=9784805308530|pages=25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nTeika chose this poem from the ''[[Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b]]'' for the hundred poems collection:\n\n{{waka|\u5c0f\u5009\u5c71\u5cf0\u306e\u3082\u307f\u3062\u8449\u5fc3\u3042\u3089\u3070|\u4eca\u3072\u3068\u305f\u3073\u306e\u884c\u5e78\u307e\u305f\u306a\u3080|reading = Ogura-yama mine no momijiba kokoro araba<br/>ima hitotabi no miyuki matanan<ref>The modern romanization of the last line would be ''miyuki '''matanamu''''' (\u201cawait the emperor's pilgrimage\u201d); by applying the [[historical kana orthography]], ''matanamu'' would be pronounced ''matana'''n'''''.</ref>|translation = Maple leaves on Ogura mountain: if you had a heart, I would have you wait for one more royal visit!<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kamens|first1=Edward|last2=Kamens|first2=Howard I.|date=1997|title=Utamakura, Allusion, and Intertextuality in Traditional Japanese Poetry|edition=illustrated|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=9780300068085|page=102}}</ref>|source = ''Sh\u016bi Wakash\u016b'' 17:1128}}\n\n==English translations==\nThe ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'' has been translated into many languages and into English many times, beginning with [[Yone Noguchi]]'s ''Hyaku Nin Isshu in English'' in 1907.<ref>Yone Noguchi, [http://www.h.ehime-u.ac.jp/-marx/YN/articles/hyakunin.htm Hyaku Nin Isshu in English, ''Waseda Bungaku'' (1907)]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOther translations include:\n* William N. Porter, ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan'' (1909)\n* Clay MacCauley, ''Hyakunin-isshu (Single Songs of a Hundred Poets)'' (1917)\n* Tom Galt, ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each'' (1982)\n* Joshua S. Mostow, ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image'' (1996)\n* Peter MacMillan, ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'' (2008; [[Penguin Classics]], revised edition 2018)\n* Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'' (2008)\n\n==Other Hyakunin Isshu anthologies==\nMany other anthologies compiled along the same criteria\u2014one hundred poems by one hundred poets\u2014include the words ''hyakunin isshu'', notably the [[World War II]]-era {{nihongo|''Aikoku Hyakunin Isshu''|\u611b\u56fd\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, or ''One Hundred Patriotic Poems by One Hundred Poets''. Also important is {{nihongo|''Ky\u014dka Hyakunin Isshu''|\u72c2\u6b4c\u767e\u4eba\u4e00\u9996}}, a series of parodies of the original ''Ogura'' collection.\n\n==Card game==\nTeika's anthology is the basis for the card game of ''[[karuta]]'', which has been popular since the [[Edo period]].<ref>[[William H. Honan|Honan, William H.]] [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/06/books/why-millions-in-japan-read-all-about-poetry.html?scp=26&sq=Donald+Keene&st=nyt  \"Why Millions in Japan Read All About Poetry,\"] ''New York Times.'' March 6, 2000.</ref>\n\nMany forms of playing games with ''Hyakunin Isshu'' exist in Japan, such as ''[[Uta-garuta]]'', the basis for [[competitive karuta]] (''ky\u014dgi karuta'').\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Nisonin]], Kyoto\n* [[Shigureden]], a museum in Kyoto about this subject\n\n==References==\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Thomas Galt. (1982). [https://books.google.com/books?id=4yuXGwAACAAJ&dq=The+Little+Treasury+of+One+Hundred+People,+One+Poem+Each&client=firefox-a  ''The Little Treasury of One Hundred People, One Poem Each.''] Princeton: [[Princeton University Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-691-06514-4}}\n* Fujiwara no Sadaie, Yoritsuna Utsunomiya, William Ninnis Porter. (1979) [https://books.google.com/books?id=1qVUaa3NtjgC&client=firefox-a  ''A Hundred Verses from Old Japan, Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu: Being a Translation of the Hyaku-nin-isshiu.''] Tokyo: [[Tuttle Publishing]]. {{ISBN|978-4-8053-0853-0}}\n* Mostow, Joshua S., ed. (1996). [https://books.google.com/books?id=U0KcAwrVksQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Pictures+of+the+Heart:+The+Hyakunin+Isshu+in+Word+and+Image.&client=firefox-a  ''Pictures of the Heart: The Hyakunin Isshu in Word and Image.''] Honolulu: [[University of Hawaii Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-8248-1705-3}}; [http://www.worldcat.org/title/pictures-of-the-heart-the-hyakunin-isshu-in-word-and-image/oclc/645187818 OCLC 645187818]\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Translation of the Ogura Hyakunin Isshu'', Peter McMillan, foreword by Donald Keene. New York: Columbia University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-231-14398-1}} <!-- http://cup.columbia.edu/book/978-0-231-14398-1/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each -->\n* ''One Hundred Poets, One Poem Each: A Treasury of Classical Japanese Verse'', Peter McMillan. London: Penguin Classics, 2018. {{ISBN|9780141395937}} <!-- https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/269418/one-hundred-poets-one-poem-each/ -->\n* ''100 Poets: Passions of the Imperial Court'', Emiko Miyashita and Michael Dylan Welch, translators. Tokyo: PIE Books, 2008. {{ISBN|978-4-89444-757-8}} <!-- http://www.piebooks.com/search/detail.php?ID=1108 -->  This book is also available as an iPad/iPhone application.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Hyakunin Isshu}}\n{{Wikisource|Ogura Hyakunin Isshu|''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu''}}\n*[http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/hyakunin/index.html ''Ogura Hyakunin Isshu - 100 Poems by 100 Poets''] at [[University of Virginia]] Library Japanese Text Initiative\n* {{librivox book | dtitle=Ogura Hyakunin Isshu | stitle=o | | author=Teika no FUJIWARA}}\n\n{{Japanese poetry}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese literature]]\n[[Category:Japanese poetry anthologies]]\n[[Category:Articles containing Japanese poems]]\n[[Category:Fujiwara no Teika]]\n", "name_user": "Poketalker", "label": "